sts that only serve as scaffolding. If the assertion fails, it looks like the appender resets, which complicates things. The placeholder test might not be necessary anymore since it doesn’t add real value. I could simply delete it to avoid clutter. However, I wonder if removing too many placeholder tests could lead to a lack of generic classes. Since we need to improve coverage, removing it seems like the best move.\\n2715:[recv] {\\\"type\\\": \\\"message_end\\\", \\\"message\\\": {\\\"role\\\": \\\"assistant\\\", \\\"content\\\": [{\\\"type\\\": \\\"thinking\\\", \\\"thinking\\\": \\\"**Analyzing Java issues**\\\\n\\\\nI’m looking into potential issues with the current Java Native Image setup. There’s a concern that class loading for `org.fusesource.jansi.AnsiConsole` might run into problems if metadata isn’t included when compiling. I need to ensure that tests generate the necessary configs, especially since improving test coverage is the task here. I also have to consider method visibility in my tests and ensure the method filtering won’t miss important overrides. Resetting streams before stopping the appender could be a concern too.\\\\n\\\\n**Considering placeholder tests**\\\\n\\\\nI’m evaluating the appender tests and whether to keep or remove placeholder tests that only serve as scaffolding. If the assertion fails, it looks like the appender resets, which complicates things. The placeholder test might not be necessary anymore since it doesn’t add real value. I could simply delete it to avoid clutter. However, I wonder if removing too many placeholder tests could lead to a lack of generic classes. Since we need to improve coverage, removing it seems like the best move.\\\\n\\\\n**Deciding on placeholder removal**\\\\n\\\\nI need to ensure that there are no issues with having \\\\\\\"all top-level test classes public,\\\\\\\" so I don't want to make unnecessary edits. Since we’ve already modified some parts, I'm leaning towards deleting the placeholder test s